OH our chapter has 4 looooovely neos: Line Three: The FOURmidable Legacy Right to left: #1 Lijia Evariz, #2 Yvette Cebrian, #3 Heather Schwartz, and #4 Ana Valenzuela i love you guys! :) so me and yo went on spring break, and it was even more eventful than we hoped. it turns out yo's window got busted and two suitcases were stolen, including all of yolanda's and yvette's clothing. yeah u read right-- we were BROKEN INTO. it was kinda unreal... so we drove all the way to cleveland with a garbage bag on the window and got it fixed there. and we got pulled over on the way and had a hard time convincing the cop that yes, yolanda owned the car and no, we didn't bust the window and steal it and yes, yolanda has a license. just not on her. whatever, i hate cops. where was he when they stole our crap? anyways we made it to cleveland. pookie's doing great, by the way. we spent a couple days at the mall getting yo some clothes and stuff. then instead of the whole williamsburg thing, we decided to head straight to philly. oh, did i mention we were driving to philly to catch the sold-out backstreet boys show at the Electric Factory? i must have. anyways, we did. it was HOT, needless to say. we waited in line, musta been 3 hours, and got in, etc. it was a really hot show, even though i couldn't hear much. they played all their old hits, and a bunch of new songs off of Never Gone (title of new album, due out June 14th... yeah, my birthday. it's not a coincidence.), including their new single Incomplete, which you should be hearing on the radio about now. if you're starting to think i'm a weirdo right now about this bsb thing... you don't wanna know anything about my 15-18 yr old days. anyways the concert was da ish, kevin pointed AND waved at me (seriously.), and it was worth every penny/mile/hour. I'm sure Yo feels the same way, so you don't even have to ask her. Hehe. quick spring break quotes, mostly from yo: "Two dollars and 50 cents! that's not a toll, that's a shakedown!" -Yo... that was before we hit the 19.00 toll in Jersey Indiana Highway Patrolman: Why were you goin' so fast? Yolanda: I'm sorry. I'm in a hurry to get out of your state. (ok, didn't really happen, but we do hate indiana.) "OK, i'm going like 66, so if anyone pulls me over, it's cuz I'm black." -Yo ***After being pulled over**** "The back of a cop car, it turns out, is the smallest place ever. And when you realize that most cops are teeny-tiny little pricks, it doesn't make sense that they get so much leg room up front." -Yo Me: Could a cop do something to you for having an attitude? Yo: They could just hit you harder. Me: You're going like way below the speed limit. Yo: I know. I don't wanna miss the one place in New Jersey where you can make a left turn. "God, does everyone who's Puerto Rican call themselves the Freakin' Puerto Rican?" -Yo "OK, we get it. You walk an empty street, you're the only one and you walk alone. Instead of Green Day it should be Green Redundant." -Me so we came back from philly, stopped off in cleveland, and came back to chicago tired as WHAT. i mean, i know i was, and i didn't even drive. so monday morning bsb were on the radio in chicago talkin about their show that night, and guess what... so they were taking listener questions so i call in and i'm like i wanna talk to bsb and they're like ok sure hold on and go back to the interview. and i'm waiting, waiting... and i hear a weird noise and then a dial tone. "omg omg omg noooooooooo" so i call back. and get through AGAIN. i'm like i wanna talk to bsb i think i got disconnected. they're like ok hold on one sec and go back to the interview. they're chit chatting with bsb for a while and it starts winding up. i'm like they better be taking some listener questions to round out the interview. they weren't. interview ended, bsb left, and i'm still on hold. i stayed on the line for like 10 minutes to be sure. so i'm not a fan of kiss 103.5 right now, except that they play my song. still not enough, but whatev. anyways, i'm over it. so since then i've been going to classes... in theory... i had a job interview, yay... i finally finished season 2 of smallville, and did i mention i hate cops? i'm REALLY over them. not that i was ever under them, smart aleck. hehe i said smart aleck. this was a LOOOOOOONG post but if i do one of these like once a month that sounds about right.

and in case you're wondering, 6 am is not me getting up early. this is me staying up late. i swear, i'm on a different clock than everyone else. i'm all whining cuz i have to be somewhere at 12:30, and my mother, for example, has been awake for 2 hours already. granted, she was like going to bed as i was waking up today, but whatever. SCORE interview friday-- eek! i need to have a chance to freaken breathe for like 2 seconds, but that's not happening anytime soon. i think my best chance will be spring break-- colonial williamsburg, what UP! revolutionary war re-enactments, here we come! wild times, i'm sure. no jk... we're actually not gonna be in colonial williamsburg, but we will be in williamsburg, VA. unless they're just two names for the same place that's stuck in the 18th century. we should be swinging by cleveland on the way to see pookie-- ...the cutest cat ever. by the way, in case y'all were wondering what yolanda would look like if she lived in colonial williamsburg, this is it: and this would be me... just kidding, i just thought that was a funny picture.

So I'm set. never mind that i've only been studying for like 5 days. and that i'm a good 10 points away from my target score. and that i'm SCREWED. on another note, if you want to get me a valentine's present, a good one would be Escada Rockin' Rio Eau de Toilette: Kinda has a corny name, but it smells good, and that's what counts. But yeah back to the LSAT thing... i wanna get into Northwestern Law, and the LSAT 25th-75th percentile range is like 166-170 (out of 180, and the median is like 150). You could almost say it's my first real studying at all, but don't say that, you'll make me feel like a slacker. hehe. OK study break over. wish me luck, pray for me, cast a spell, do whatever you gotta do to GET ME THAT 170!

so i went home for thanksgiving last weekend. it was a lot of fun, especially spending time with my dad's side of the family on Thanksgiving. There seem to be two factions within the family: those who eat chitlins (usually the older generation, i.e. my parents, aunts and uncles)... and those who find them DISGUSTING. I'm in the latter, needless to say. Ew. Chitterlings, a.k.a. Chitlins are a PIG'S small INTESTINE! Of all the parts of the pig to eat! And if you've ever been around them, you know what the smell is like. My uncle Joe: What would Thanksgiving be without chitlins? Me: It would smell a lot better, for one. My cousin Kim: There should be a caution label: WARNING--May cause stankin' breath. My mom: You know, you could lose weight eating chitlins. My brother Andre: How, by puking 'em back up? Hehe. We're funny. Anyways, people kept coming around us with their smelly plates of chitlins and it reminded me of the old saying: "I am not a Chitlin' eater; But a Chitlin' eater's son. Someone else can eat de Chitlin's 'Til de Chitlin' eater comes!" Food for thought? Anyways, now I'm fully into the swing of the christmas season. I've already bought a few presents, I decorated the tree on Friday, and I'm currently in the process of burning the DEFINITIVE Christmas Collection 3-Disc Mix CD. You name a classic/wonderful/amazing Christmas song, and it's on there. For 5 bucks, I'll burn you a copy. Oh, and there's this little thing called FINALS. But i've pretty much given up on tests, classes, and college in general.

A recent survey by the Program on International Policy Attitudes at the University of Maryland found that nearly 70 percent of President Bush's supporters believe the U.S. has come up with "clear evidence" that Saddam Hussein was working closely with Al Qaeda. A third of the president's supporters believe weapons of mass destruction were found in Iraq. And more than a third believe that a substantial majority of world opinion supported the U.S.-led invasion. This is scary. How do you make a rational political pitch to people who have put that part of their brain on hold? No wonder Bush won." -Bob Herbert, "Voting Without the Facts" in the New York Times, November 8, 2004 Ah, well, I've gotten over it... at least I KNOW he won't be re-elected next time. Or will he try to amend the constitution about that, too? At least Obeezy won. *sigh*... I heart him!

so i'm at work at the black house, and apparently the steady stream of people coming to visit me has finally died down, and so the boredom has set in. i LUV barack obama. he's so adorable and fun and he's so smart... mainly when he's standing next to alan keyes. i was watching the obama/ alan keyes debate earlier and i swear i laughed out loud no fewer than 10 times at the things keyes was saying, and to my knowledge he never deliberately made a joke. he's got some ridiculous views, and the most hilarious part of it is that he's not lying or playing politics-- he really believes these things. it's kind of sad, really. i can't decide what cracks me up about him more-- the opinions he has or the fact that he looks like some sort of rare species of amphibian. like a cross between a poisonous jungle frog and the gecko from the geico commercials. it's uncanny. moving on, i'm failing all my classes, you'll be happy to know. my bank account is devastatingly overdrawn. I HAVEN'T DECLARED MY MAJOR. my life seems to be falling apart in every possible way right now. it's getting hard to be optimistic... but then i think about the HOT lip gloss i bought on saturday (incidentally, the transaction that threw my account into the negative) and somehow... everything's OK. in political news, bush is up five points in the cnn/usatoday/gallup poll going into the home stretch- the last 7 days of the campaign. i, however, get my political information from the daily show, where jon stewart sticks pin in his voodoo version of bush between segments. biased? Maybe. awesome? absolutely! i'll leave you with my favorite question to alan keyes at tonight's debate: Reporter: Mr. Keyes... you have run for 2 different U.S. Senate positions and in two different presidential elections, without ever even coming close to winning. Is there a point where this behavior ceases to be useful? Keyes: Der... uhhh... I like to lose? (Not his real answer; I wasn't paying attention.) Obama: (smug chuckling in background)

If America were Iraq, What would it be Like? by Juan Cole President Bush said Tuesday that the Iraqis are refuting the pessimists and implied that things are improving in that country. What would America look like if it were in Iraq's current situation? The population of the US is over 11 times that of Iraq, so a lot of statistics would have to be multiplied by that number. Thus, violence killed 300 Iraqis last week, the equivalent proportionately of 3,300 Americans. What if 3,300 Americans had died in car bombings, grenade and rocket attacks, machine gun spray, and aerial bombardment in the last week? That is a number greater than the deaths on September 11, and if America were Iraq, it would be an ongoing, weekly or monthly toll. And what if those deaths occurred all over the country, including in the capital of Washington, DC, but mainly above the Mason Dixon line, in Boston, Minneapolis, Salt Lake City, and San Francisco? What if the grounds of the White House and the government buildings near the Mall were constantly taking mortar fire? What if almost nobody in the State Department at Foggy Bottom, the White House, or the Pentagon dared venture out of their buildings, and considered it dangerous to go over to Crystal City or Alexandria? What if all the reporters for all the major television and print media were trapped in five-star hotels in Washington, DC and New York, unable to move more than a few blocks safely, and dependent on stringers to know what was happening in Oklahoma City and St. Louis? What if the only time they ventured into the Midwest was if they could be embedded in Army or National Guard units? There are estimated to be some 25,000 guerrillas in Iraq engaged in concerted acts of violence. What if there were private armies totalling 275,000 men, armed with machine guns, assault rifles (legal again!), rocket-propelled grenades, and mortar launchers, hiding out in dangerous urban areas of cities all over the country? What if they completely controlled Seattle, Portland, San Francisco, Salt Lake City, Las Vegas, Denver and Omaha, such that local police and Federal troops could not go into those cities? What if, during the past year, the Secretary of State (Aqilah Hashemi), the President (Izzedine Salim), and the Attorney General (Muhammad Baqir al-Hakim) had all been assassinated? What if all the cities in the US were wracked by a crime wave, with thousands of murders, kidnappings, burglaries, and carjackings in every major city every year? What if the Air Force routinely (I mean daily or weekly) bombed Billings, Montana, Flint, Michigan, Watts in Los Angeles, Philadelphia, Anacostia in Washington, DC, and other urban areas, attempting to target "safe houses" of "criminal gangs", but inevitably killing a lot of children and little old ladies? What if, from time to time, the US Army besieged Virginia Beach, killing hundreds of armed members of the Christian Soldiers? What if entire platoons of the Christian Soldiers militia holed up in Arlington National Cemetery, and were bombarded by US Air Force warplanes daily, destroying thousands of graves and even pulverizing the Vietnam Memorial over on the Mall? What if the National Council of Churches had to call for a popular march of thousands of believers to converge on the National Cathedral to stop the US Army from demolishing it to get at a rogue band of the Timothy McVeigh Memorial Brigades? What if there were virtually no commercial air traffic in the country? What if many roads were highly dangerous, especially Interstate 95 from Richmond to Washington, DC, and I-95 and I-91 up to Boston? If you got on I-95 anywhere along that over 500-mile stretch, you would risk being carjacked, kidnapped, or having your car sprayed with machine gun fire. What if no one had electricity for much more than 10 hours a day, and often less? What if it went off at unpredictable times, causing factories to grind to a halt and air conditioning to fail in the middle of the summer in Houston and Miami? What if the Alaska pipeline were bombed and disabled at least monthly? What if unemployment hovered around 40%? What if veterans of militia actions at Ruby Ridge and the Oklahoma City bombing were brought in to run the government on the theory that you need a tough guy in these times of crisis? What if municipal elections were cancelled and cliques close to the new "president" quietly installed in the statehouses as "governors?" What if several of these governors (especially of Montana and Wyoming) were assassinated soon after taking office or resigned when their children were taken hostage by guerrillas? What if the leader of the European Union maintained that the citizens of the United States are, under these conditions, refuting pessimism and that freedom and democracy are just around the corner?

first and foremost-- i did it. i got my tattoo, so take THAT all you naysayers. well i mean it's not like i'm the tattoo "type", if there is such a thing, so i can understand your naysaying. anyways, i got it, and it's DA ISH: it's not all red, that's just my sunburnt shoulder blade. what UP lady on the moon! and YES, it hurts, but maybe that's just because i'm a wimp... whatever, i got a tattoo-- how wimpy does that make me? but mainly the pain was in little intervals, and it feels kind of like a burn, only probably worse, at times. hehe, now i'm acting like some kind of expert. other than that, i was in BG and we went out and stuff-- people are WAY better looking there! the guys are all like super hot and they run around playing football all the time. NU sucks. Yo says they're all cuter cuz they're all dumber, but I disagree. They can't ALL be dumber, but they were ALL CUTER. and, BGSU being a bigger school, there were so many MORE of them. Come on, Northwestern guys, get it together. Downside (because there always is one): the girls are cuter too. but only slightly, and it may have just been the lighting. anyways, i've got three days until i go to chicago. what's really going on? what happened to the summer? why am I up at 7am? whatev i'm soo glad to be getting back to evanston it's sick. to set up my room in KEMPER (did i mention that's where i'm living?), walk around campus, and be somewhere besides cleveland. i've been here so long the cleveland air is creating a filmy layer of clevelandness on my body, and we can't have that. i came across this really sweet emily dickinson poem today: 08 - Not In Vain If I can stop one heart from breaking, I shall not live in vain; If I can ease one life the aching, Or cool one pain, Or help one fainting robin Unto his nest again, I shall not live in vain. isn't that nice? doesn't it make you want to go do some volunteering? there's a bunch of dickinson poems at this site: http://amblesideonline.homestead.com/EmilyDickinson.html. I really like her poetry because I like poems that make you want to go take a walk in the woods or make you feel like you're in another place, seeing different things. anyways, i got the smallville season 2 dvd, and more importantly, SMALLVILLE SEASON 4 STARTS SEPTEMBER 22. dude, NOTHING could make me miss it. NOTHING. and in case u were wondering, there WILL be a smallville kick-off party and it WILL be in Kemper and you ARE invited. feel free to bring snacks and stuff, and remember there's no talking when Tom is onscreen. ta-ta for now

So i'm at work all the rest of this week. yeah, at the DNC. it's really not a fun job, except for I get to talk politics for like 10 hours a day. If you consider that fun. And I don't think I do. Basically, I go up to someone's door, knock, and tell them I'm with the DNC and we're trying to beat Bush and elect Kerry this November. And if they're Republican, I dodge the baseball bat and tell them to have a nice day. If they're not, I proceed to tell them why they should give me money right then, preferably in the form of a $100 check made payable to the DNC. This is something I really suck at. It's amazing I've lasted this long at the job. Like they tell us not to take "no" for an answer, but I don't think "no" is that bad. As long as I don't have to stand there and try to convince them over the sound of their barking dogs that the DNC needs their Social Security check more than they do. But it's OK, Friday's my last day. I'm thinkin I need like a week or two to chill/shop before I start getting ready for school. It's really not that bad of a job, apart from the actual "working" part of it. in other news, the olympics are on. and in addition to my eternal respect for male gymnasts, for being so hot, and being able to perform on those ring thingies: i also have gained a newfound love for synchronized springboard. I had never seen it before, but it's SO cool. it's so awesome; they look like conjoined twins. anyways, that's me for now. four days till i'm FREE...

it's like... always there.  and then i try to ignore it and every few days or so it's like HERE I AM!  just reminding you... i never dreamed, 8 years ago in 7th or 8th grade that time would stand still.  but it did.  how  can something so common be so rare?  how can something that should be there... fail to exist?  is that even possible? when is it going to switch on... the day, hour, moment when the present becomes The Past... and nothing matters as much as it did then, and nothing that mattered then can compare to what matters now.  a new set of issues.  but how does that just happen?  and be real life?  maybe it can be worked through the developmental model of progress-- i mean industrialization doesn't "just happen", does it? so there are stages... processes that must be followed and must not be skipped. is it even worth it anymore? can't life just... be? well there's the developmental model... it must be followed, so u can't just let go.  u have to follow it exactly, and then BAM! industrialization.  don't ask questions, don't take shortcuts, and maybe one day you'll have indoor plumbing and all that.  but probably not, cuz you'll get ahead of yourself and forget something. after years and years... what a waste.  time, money, effort, emotion-- all gone.  but i guess like they say... the time would have passed anyway, the money would have been spent somehow, etc. and emotion is way overrated.

so back to me hating my job.


i work as a cashier, but sometimes i feel more like a vending machine:

me: Hi!
customer: (silence.)
me: That'll be 4.25.
customer: (silence, hands me money)
me: Out of ten?
customer: (silence.)
me: 6.75 is your change. Have a good day!
customer: um, you only gave me 5.75.
me: That's a dollar coin.  
customer: (walks away, in silence.)

but i mean the reason i have a job outweighs the myriad of reasons my job SUCKS. I mean, at least this year i'm not THAT CHICK.  Last year I was THAT CHICK.  THAT CHICK doesn't have a job, even though all her friends do.  THAT CHICK whines about how bored she is, how much she misses school, how she's going to decorate her dorm room, etc.  THAT CHICK buys pillows with money she doesn't have and promises herself that she'll clean her room TOMORROW. THAT CHICK is going nowhere fast.  Are you THAT CHICK??

Well I'm not... but is it worth it?
